  "meta": {
    "title": "Dependence Logic",
    "description": "Dependence logic is an extension of first-order logic which adds to it dependence atoms , that is, expressions of the form \\(\\eqord(x_1 \\ldots x_n, y)\\) which assert that the value of \\(y\\) is functionally dependent on (in other words, determined by) the values of \\(x_1 \\ldots x_n\\). These atoms permit the specification of non-linearly ordered dependency patterns between variables, much in the same sense of IF-Logic slashed quantifiers ; but, differently from IF-logic, dependence logic separates quantification from the specification of such dependence/independence conditions. The principal semantics of dependence logic, called team semantics , generalizes Tarski's semantics by letting expressions be satisfied or not satisfied with respect to sets of variable assignments rather than with respect to single assignments. This semantics pre-dates the development of dependence logic proper, and it was originally developed by Wilfrid Hodges in the context of IF-logic (Hodges 1997). There also exists a game-theoretic semantics for dependence logic, based on games of imperfect information and roughly analogous to the game-theoretic semantics for independence-friendly logic (V&auml;&auml;n&auml;nen 2007a). Sensu stricto , the term \"dependence logic\" refers exclusively to the language obtained by adding the above-mentioned functional dependence atoms to the language of first-order logic; but the term is also used, in a more general sense, to refer to the area of research that studies the properties of logics obtained by adding various notions of dependence and independence to first order logic, such as independence logic (Gr&auml;del & V&auml;&auml;n&auml;nen 2013), intuitionistic dependence logic (Yang 2013) or inclusion logic (Galliani 2012, Galliani & Hella 2013), or even those of logics extending other logical frameworks through similar atoms, as in the case of modal dependence logic (V&auml;&auml;n&auml;nen 2008). In this article, the term \"dependence logic\" will be used to refer to dependence logic proper, and the term \"logics of dependence and independence\" will instead be used to refer to its variants and generalizations.",
    "version": "1.0.0",
    "dateCreated": "2026-03-22T05:13:40.486Z",
    "dateModified": "2026-03-22T05:13:40.486Z",
    "datePublished": "2017-02-22T13:00:00.000Z",
    "keywords": [
      "compositionality",
      "game semantics pragmatics",
      "logic classical",
      "logic games",
      "logic higher order",
      "logic if"
    ]
  },
  "problemSolved": {
    "statement": "Dependence logic is an extension of first-order logic which adds to it dependence atoms , that is, expressions of the form \\(\\eqord(x_1 \\ldots x_n, y)\\) which assert that the value of \\(y\\) is functionally dependent on (in other words, determined by) the values of \\(x_1 \\ldots x_n\\). These atoms permit the specification of non-linearly ordered dependency patterns between variables, much in the same sense of IF-Logic slashed quantifiers ; but, differently from IF-logic, dependence logic separates quantification from the specification of such dependence/independence conditions. The principal semantics of dependence logic, called team semantics , generalizes Tarski's semantics by letting expressions be satisfied or not satisfied with respect to sets of variable assignments rather than with respect to single assignments. This semantics pre-dates the development of dependence logic proper, and it was originally developed by Wilfrid Hodges in the context of IF-logic (Hodges 1997). There also exists a game-theoretic semantics for dependence logic, based on games of imperfect information and roughly analogous to the game-theoretic semantics for independence-friendly logic (V&auml;&auml;n&auml;nen 2007a). Sensu stricto , the term \"dependence logic\" refers exclusively to the language obtained by adding the above-mentioned functional dependence atoms to the language of first-order logic; but the term is also used, in a more general sense, to refer to the area of research that studies the properties of logics obtained by adding various notions of dependence and independence to first order logic, such as independence logic (Gr&auml;del & V&auml;&auml;n&auml;nen 2013), intuitionistic dependence logic (Yang 2013) or inclusion logic (Galliani 2012, Galliani & Hella 2013), or even those of logics extending other logical frameworks through similar atoms, as in the case of modal dependence logic (V&auml;&auml;n&auml;nen 2008). In this article, the term \"dependence logic\" will be used to refer to dependence logic proper, and the term \"logics of dependence and independence\" will instead be used to refer to its variants and generalizations.",
    "context": "Opening section: 1. Dependency patterns in first order logic and its extensions | Related entries: compositionality, game-semantics-pragmatics, logic-games, logic-classical, logic-if, logic-higher-order",
